




TY  - JOUR
T1  - The Time Variation in Risk Appetite and Uncertainty
AU  - Bekaert, Geert
AU  - Engstrom, Eric C.
AU  - Xu, Nancy R.
Y1  - 2021/10/05
PY  - 2021
DA  - 2022/06/01
N1  - doi: 10.1287/mnsc.2021.4068
DO  - 10.1287/mnsc.2021.4068
T2  - Management Science
JF  - Management Science
JO  - Management Science
SP  - 3975
EP  - 4004
VL  - 68
IS  - 6
PB  - INFORMS
N2  - We formulate a dynamic no-arbitrage asset pricing model for equities and corporate bonds, featuring time variation in both risk aversion and economic uncertainty. The joint dynamics among cash flows, macroeconomic fundamentals, and risk aversion accommodate both heteroskedasticity and non-Gaussianity. The model delivers measures of risk aversion and uncertainty at the daily frequency. We verify that equity variance risk premiums are very informative about risk aversion, whereas credit spreads and corporate bond volatility are highly correlated with economic uncertainty. Our model-implied risk premiums outperform standard instruments for predicting asset excess returns. Risk aversion is substantially correlated with consumer confidence measures and in early 2020 reacted more strongly to new COVID cases than did an uncertainty proxy.This paper was accepted by Haoxiang Zhu, finance.
AB  - We formulate a dynamic no-arbitrage asset pricing model for equities and corporate bonds, featuring time variation in both risk aversion and economic uncertainty. The joint dynamics among cash flows, macroeconomic fundamentals, and risk aversion accommodate both heteroskedasticity and non-Gaussianity. The model delivers measures of risk aversion and uncertainty at the daily frequency. We verify that equity variance risk premiums are very informative about risk aversion, whereas credit spreads and corporate bond volatility are highly correlated with economic uncertainty. Our model-implied risk premiums outperform standard instruments for predicting asset excess returns. Risk aversion is substantially correlated with consumer confidence measures and in early 2020 reacted more strongly to new COVID cases than did an uncertainty proxy.This paper was accepted by Haoxiang Zhu, finance.
